We first extract the three pieces of information needed from the provided schedules.

1. Debt to Asset Ratio  
 • Total Liabilities: From the balance sheet, the only liabilities given are the “Accounts Payable” and “Taxes Payable.” Their End_amount values are  
  Accounts Payable = 545000.00  
  Taxes Payable = 284755.77  
 • Therefore, Total Liabilities = 545000.00 + 284755.77 = 829755.77  
 • Total Assets (End_amount) = 15023526.85  
 • Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets = 829755.77 / 15023526.85 ≈ 0.0552  
 • Rounding to two decimal places, we report this ratio as 0.06.

2. Gross Profit Margin  
 • From the income statement,  
  Gross Profit = 2610115.02  
  Total Revenue = 5695115.02  
 • Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (2610115.02 / 5695115.02) × 100 ≈ 45.82%  
 • We express the result as “45.82%.”

3. Operating Cash Flow Ratio  
 • The Operating Cash Flow Ratio is computed using the Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities divided by Total Current Liabilities.  
 • From the cash flow statement,  
  Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –224133.22  
 • From the balance sheet,  
  Total Current Liabilities = 829755.77  
 • Operating Cash Flow Ratio = –224133.22 / 829755.77 ≈ –0.2701  
 • Rounding to two decimals, we report this as –0.27.

Thus, the final answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.06",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "45.82%",
    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-0.27"
  }
}
